		<title>Pitchdrive Raises €60M for AI-Native Ventures</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/pitchdrive-raises-e60m-for-ai-native-ventures/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 09 Jun 2026 14:43:19 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=202645</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Pitchdrive has officially announced the final closing of its fourth investment fund, Fund IV, at €60 million. The fund deliberately blew past its original target of €50 million due to</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/pitchdrive-raises-e60m-for-ai-native-ventures/" data-wpel-link="internal">Pitchdrive Raises €60M for AI-Native Ventures</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.pitchdrive.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Pitchdrive </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has officially announced the final closing of its fourth </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/beacon-software-raises-225m-series-c-for-ai-roll-up/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">investment </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">fund, Fund IV, at €60 million. The fund deliberately blew past its original target of €50 million due to intense investor demand, positioning the firm to aggressively back Europe&#8217;s emerging cohort of AI-native software and hardware startups.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">In a departure from the typical European venture capital playbook, Fund IV was entirely privately backed. The capital raised was exclusively from tech entrepreneurs, seasoned operators, and prominent family offices, completely turning away institutional fund-of-funds or government-backed institutional capital.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">According to Pitchdrive, total subscription interest exceeded €85 million within weeks of launching. However, the partnership made the strategic decision to reject roughly €25 million in additional allocations, capping the fund firmly at €60 million to keep their localised, highly concentrated operational thesis intact.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Capitalizing on the Co-founder Capital Model</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2020 by Belgian entrepreneurs Wim Derkinderen, Boris Bogaert, and Koen Christiaens, Pitchdrive has gained an industry reputation for its strict Co-founder Capital framework. Rather than acting as passive financial backers, the firm embeds a deeply technical network of over 20 active European operators directly onto the cap tables of its portfolio investments.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202646" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202646" class="size-large wp-image-202646" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/AI-4-1024x576.jpg" alt="AI" width="1024" height="576" /><p id="caption-attachment-202646" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The advisory ecosystem includes founders and executives from several of Europe’s most successful technology companies, such as team.blue, Deliverect, Lighthouse, Loop Earplugs, Showpad, Teamleader, Silverfin, and Foodbag. The network is chaired by Jonas Dhaenens, the founder of the European hosting unicorn team.blue.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;When we built team.blue, the kind of investor I wished I’d had on day one simply didn&#8217;t exist in Europe,&#8221; said Dhaenens in a statement regarding the close. &#8220;That is exactly what Pitchdrive represents: a venture firm run entirely by operators who have already sat in the founder’s seat. Fund IV is designed to double down on that exact philosophy: stay small, stay close to the product, and remain hyper-disciplined.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/beacon-software-raises-225m-series-c-for-ai-roll-up/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Beacon Software Raises $225M Series C for AI Roll-Up</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Reality of Early-Stage AI Infrastructure Costs</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The expansion of Pitchdrive&#8217;s capital pool from its previous €40 million fund highlights a fundamental shift in early-stage tech valuations. As artificial intelligence becomes the core architecture of new software infrastructure, the baseline capital requirements to build a minimum viable product have dramatically outpaced standard pre-seed funding.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;The early-stage venture market has fundamentally reset,&#8221; explained Boris Bogaert, co-founder and general partner at Pitchdrive. &#8220;What we are seeing on the ground is that pre-seed capital is heavily shifting from human headcount to computing tokens. AI-native companies scale incredibly fast, but their initial computing infrastructure and API costs require significantly larger upfront ticket sizes.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To adjust to this reality, Pitchdrive is scaling its individual ticket allocation, planning to deploy checks ranging from €250,000 to €3 million per startup. The fund expects to back a concentrated group of 25 to 30 early-stage companies over the next 24 months, maintaining a tight portfolio to ensure high-touch operational mentorship.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Filtering the AI Wrapper Noise</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Pitchdrive’s investment thesis for Fund IV runs through a strict, specialised filter. The firm explicitly stated it will bypass generic &#8220;AI for X&#8221; software wrappers that lack proprietary data advantages, as well as companies bolting on AI buzzwords purely to attract superficial venture interest.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Instead, Fund IV is targeting three core domains:</span></p>
<ol>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>AI-Native Software:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Products built from scratch around machine learning infrastructure that could not physically exist in a previous software generation.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>AI-Enabled Business Operations:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Applications that fundamentally alter the unit economics and delivery costs of traditional service sectors.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Software-Driven Physical Industries:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> High-growth hardware spaces, including advanced robotics, logistics, and localised mobility solutions.</span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Demonstrating its readiness to look beyond continental Europe for top-tier machine learning talent, Pitchdrive also disclosed its participation in a $10 million pre-seed round for ZeroDrift, a New York-based compliance AI startup. The deal, co-invested alongside Silicon Valley heavyweight Andreessen Horowitz (a16z), marks Pitchdrive’s official entry into the competitive US tech market and signals that its operator-led investment model is gaining global traction.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/pitchdrive-raises-e60m-for-ai-native-ventures/" data-wpel-link="internal">Pitchdrive Raises €60M for AI-Native Ventures</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
